						<!-- Textual Information -->
						<section class="post">
							<header class="major">
								<h1>Understanding Exceptions in Java</h1>
								<p>In Java, an exception is an event that disrupts the normal flow of the program's instructions. Exceptions can be caused by various issues such as input/output errors, network failures, or unexpected user input. Java provides a robust mechanism to handle exceptions and maintain the stability of applications.</p>
							</header>
							<p>There are two types of exceptions in Java:</p>
							<ul>
								<li><strong>Checked Exceptions:</strong> These are exceptions that are checked at compile-time. Examples include IOException and SQLException.</li>
								<li><strong>Unchecked Exceptions:</strong> These exceptions occur at runtime. Examples include NullPointerException and ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException.</li>
							</ul>
						</section>

